<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>I Feel So Sorry for My A.I. Sunglasses</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/14/magazine/ai-sunglasses-meta-zuckerberg.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/14/magazine/ai-sunglasses-meta-zuckerberg.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/14/magazine/ai-sunglasses-meta-zuckerberg.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Plenty of people hate Mark Zuckerberg’s superintelligent, supercharged spectacles. I was ready to hate them, too.</description><dc:creator>Sam Anderson</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 14 Apr 2026 09:02:12 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Wearable Computing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sunglasses</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Camera</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/04/12/magazine/12mag-ididit/12mag-ididit-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Photo illustration by Joe Lingeman</media:credit></media:content></item><item><title>Paul Brainerd Dies at 78; Pioneered Desktop Publishing With PageMaker</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/03/21/technology/personaltech/paul-brainerd-dead.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/03/21/technology/personaltech/paul-brainerd-dead.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/03/21/technology/personaltech/paul-brainerd-dead.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>His software brought printing into the digital age, allowing users to stop manually splicing columns of text and graphics and instead create layouts on a virtual pasteboard.</description><dc:creator>Michael S. Rosenwald</dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 21 Mar 2026 16:14:24 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Paul Brainerd</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Obituary</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Publishing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Software</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Desktop computer</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Printing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Word processor</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Aldus</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Apple</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Adobe</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/03/23/multimedia/19Brainard-02-wmhq/19Brainard-02-wmhq-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v2.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>IslandWood</media:credit><media:description>Mr. Brainerd in an undated photo. After Aldus merged with Adobe Systems in 1994, he left the company and devoted the rest of his life to philanthropy, especially environmental conservation efforts in the Pacific Northwest.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta to Lay Off 10 Percent of Work Force in A.I. Push</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/meta-layoffs.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/meta-layoffs.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/meta-layoffs.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The layoffs affect about 8,000 employees, with Meta also planning to close 6,000 open roles, as the company focuses on artificial intelligence.</description><dc:creator>Mike Isaac and Eli Tan</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 18:01:08 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Layoffs</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Furloughs</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">internal-open-access-from-nl</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/04/23/multimedia/23biz-meta-layoffs-mcqf/23biz-meta-layoffs-mcqf-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Noah Berger/Associated Press</media:credit><media:description>Meta’s headquarters in Menlo Park, Calif.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Elon Musk and Sam Altman’s Epic Fight Heads to Court</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/elon-musk-sam-altman-openai-trial.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/elon-musk-sam-altman-openai-trial.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/elon-musk-sam-altman-openai-trial.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A jury trial that is set to start on Monday could shift the course of the A.I. race, with Mr. Musk seeking billions of dollars in damages from Mr. Altman’s OpenAI.</description><dc:creator>Cade Metz</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 16:31:57 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Elon Musk</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sam Altman</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Lawsuits</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Yvonne Gonzalez Rogers</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Greg Brockman</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/04/08/multimedia/biz-musk-openai-03-wpgf/biz-musk-openai-03-wpgf-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Eric Lee for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Mr. Musk in February with Shivon Zilis, the mother of four of his children and a former OpenAI board member. She is expected to testify at the trial.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Aging in Place: How Technology Might Help You Grow Old at Home</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/22/business/seniors-home-care-tech.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/22/business/seniors-home-care-tech.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/22/business/seniors-home-care-tech.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The budding field is turning dreams into reality for older adults who are eager to age in place, filling caregiving gaps and easing minds as America ages rapidly.</description><dc:creator>Susan Shain</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 22 Apr 2026 09:00:08 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Old age</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">elderly</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">senior citizens</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Elderly care</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Geriatrics</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Robot</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Startup</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Privacy</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">AARP</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">US</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/03/24/00caregiving-AgeTech-01-85122-cover/00caregiving-AgeTech-01-85122-cover-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image" /></item><item><title>OpenAI Unveils Its New, More Powerful GPT-5.5 Model</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/openai-new-model.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/openai-new-model.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/23/technology/openai-new-model.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The maker of ChatGPT is taking a more open approach to cybersecurity than its chief rival, Anthropic.</description><dc:creator>Cade Metz</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 18:00:06 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computer security</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Hacker (computer security)</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">ChatGPT</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/04/23/business/23biz-openai-model-1/23biz-openai-model-1-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Gabby Jones/Bloomberg</media:credit><media:description>OpenAI said its new technology was better at writing computer code and tasks related to other office work.</media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>